WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.440
Just need to maximize.

00:00:06.680 --> 00:00:07.520
Okay.

00:00:09.800 --> 00:00:11.760
Hello, good morning.

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:14.160
My name is Andrew Holz, as Daniel said,

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:16.040
and I'm here to talk to you.

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:18.000
The title of my talk is Oops I'm A Manager

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:20.559
on Minimum Viable Process.

00:00:20.559 --> 00:00:22.400
In the startup world, a lot of times MVP

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:23.719
meant minimum viable product,

00:00:23.719 --> 00:00:25.139
so I'm kind of stealing that

00:00:25.139 --> 00:00:27.879
to talk about minimum viable process.

00:00:28.879 --> 00:00:31.400
So before I kind of get into the topic,

00:00:31.400 --> 00:00:33.439
I'd like to just introduce myself just a little bit

00:00:33.439 --> 00:00:35.080
and say, hey, why oops?

00:00:35.080 --> 00:00:36.720
Why, what is that oops in your title?

00:00:36.720 --> 00:00:38.060
That's a little odd, right?

00:00:38.060 --> 00:00:42.160
So currently I am a head of engineering for open source.

00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:44.439
I have the privilege of working with some amazing teams,

00:00:44.439 --> 00:00:47.560
the Shiny team, the Cordo team, MLverse team,

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:50.599
newly emerging tiny tools team, and it's been great.

00:00:50.599 --> 00:00:53.599
But if we scroll the calendar back 25,

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:55.720
a little more than that years,

00:00:55.720 --> 00:00:59.520
I was at Bell Labs, second job out of school.

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:01.480
I was working with GIS data

00:01:01.480 --> 00:01:03.060
in the loop surveillance department,

00:01:03.060 --> 00:01:04.720
having a good time doing that.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:07.919
But things change at big companies, situations change,

00:01:07.919 --> 00:01:10.320
and they decided to spin out

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:12.199
several of the products in that department.

00:01:12.199 --> 00:01:15.040
A bunch of senior devs were taking over that stuff,

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:16.239
starting a company to do it,

00:01:16.239 --> 00:01:18.800
and they recruited me to join along.

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:21.239
So I was excited, joined them,

00:01:21.239 --> 00:01:23.320
about a dozen engineers, as I said,

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:25.199
like some grizzled, experienced folks,

00:01:25.199 --> 00:01:28.379
five, 10, 15, 20 years more experience than I had.

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:31.519
And then they started organizing things,

00:01:31.519 --> 00:01:33.800
and I was kind of continuing on my data stuff

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:35.959
and playing around with Oracle, good times.

00:01:37.279 --> 00:01:38.639
And there was like,

00:01:38.639 --> 00:01:40.599
oh, well, we need to get a little more organized,

00:01:40.599 --> 00:01:43.199
and we need to do a little bit of this management function.

00:01:43.199 --> 00:01:45.720
And pretty much all the other engineers that were there

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:48.500
took a big step back, like, oh, management,

00:01:48.500 --> 00:01:50.040
no, not for me, no thank you.

00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:52.660
And I was like, well, I have a psych major

00:01:52.699 --> 00:01:53.980
that went with my CS degree.

00:01:53.980 --> 00:01:56.059
Hey, maybe I could do that stuff.

00:01:56.059 --> 00:01:58.260
So I stepped into that.

00:01:58.260 --> 00:01:59.540
We built the company up.

00:01:59.540 --> 00:02:01.820
I got to do a whole tons of crazy stuff,

00:02:01.820 --> 00:02:03.300
maybe earlier than I should have,

00:02:03.300 --> 00:02:04.620
but it was a great experience.

00:02:04.620 --> 00:02:06.900
We sold the company, $20 million.

00:02:06.900 --> 00:02:09.020
And ever since then, it's been great.

00:02:09.020 --> 00:02:11.779
I've been doing various technical leadership roles

00:02:11.779 --> 00:02:14.100
at small companies, my own startups,

00:02:14.100 --> 00:02:17.419
other people's, bigger companies, all on the way.

00:02:17.419 --> 00:02:19.020
And it's been a great journey.

00:02:19.020 --> 00:02:21.460
One of the big things I learned during that journey

00:02:21.460 --> 00:02:25.899
is I love, absolutely love, helping other people level up

00:02:25.899 --> 00:02:27.660
and find those people that are looking

00:02:27.660 --> 00:02:30.860
to be a force multiplier, that are part of the team,

00:02:30.860 --> 00:02:32.660
that understand the context,

00:02:32.660 --> 00:02:35.020
and want to help the team do its best work,

00:02:35.020 --> 00:02:37.479
be a multiplier for other people on the team.

00:02:37.479 --> 00:02:38.899
So really enjoy that.

00:02:38.899 --> 00:02:41.300
I'm here to talk to you today with that in mind,

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:45.160
and to talk a little bit about ways you might get into that.

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:46.699
Thinking back to some of the other folks

00:02:46.699 --> 00:02:48.339
that had spoken earlier,

00:02:48.339 --> 00:02:50.619
essentially, this is about exploring,

00:02:50.619 --> 00:02:52.660
is that niche of leadership

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:54.699
and helping the team do their best work,

00:02:54.699 --> 00:02:56.259
a niche that's good for you?

00:02:56.259 --> 00:02:57.419
Maybe you're already on it.

00:02:57.419 --> 00:02:59.619
Oops, I oopsed my way into management

00:02:59.619 --> 00:03:01.039
and have really enjoyed it.

00:03:01.039 --> 00:03:02.139
Maybe you're considering it.

00:03:02.139 --> 00:03:03.740
Maybe you've already been oopsed.

00:03:03.740 --> 00:03:04.860
Hopefully this is a little way

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:06.580
to help kind of get that all started.

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:10.139
So in my personal experience and things I've observed,

00:03:10.139 --> 00:03:12.779
a lot of leadership, you started doing it,

00:03:12.779 --> 00:03:14.820
you were interested, you were helping out,

00:03:14.820 --> 00:03:16.860
and then it becomes your role over time.

00:03:16.860 --> 00:03:20.580
You actually do the job partially before you get the job.

00:03:20.580 --> 00:03:23.740
So battlefield promotions, it's not so planned.

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:25.500
You can kind of back into it,

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:27.979
but very few organizations give people much support.

00:03:27.979 --> 00:03:30.179
So this is just a little taste of that

00:03:30.179 --> 00:03:31.259
and some of the other things here.

00:03:31.259 --> 00:03:33.460
It's exciting that you're all here to talk about it

00:03:33.460 --> 00:03:37.020
and hopefully are considering that kind of an opportunity.

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:39.320
And then frankly, a lot of leadership training

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:42.759
can be really dry and takes itself so seriously.

00:03:42.759 --> 00:03:45.460
So Dr. Seuss, a little bit cheeky.

00:03:45.460 --> 00:03:46.520
That's what I'm going for here.

00:03:47.179 --> 00:03:48.440
We'll see how it all plays out.

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:50.559
Okay, let's get onto the topic at hand.

00:03:50.559 --> 00:03:51.960
Minimum viable process.

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:54.080
Let's take those in the reverse order

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:56.240
and talk a little bit about each of those words.

00:03:56.240 --> 00:03:58.320
So process is just how shit gets done.

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:00.720
That's like the overall, we have to be effective.

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:03.119
We have some needs, we do some stuff,

00:04:03.119 --> 00:04:04.520
we deliver out some results.

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:06.720
Hopefully the organization's happy with it.

00:04:07.639 --> 00:04:09.440
It also needs to be viable, right?

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:10.639
Big word there.

00:04:10.639 --> 00:04:13.679
Obviously it means effective in those steps

00:04:13.679 --> 00:04:15.520
that we're taking to get stuff done.

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:18.779
But I think it also implies really importantly sustainable.

00:04:19.779 --> 00:04:21.679
If you don't have a sustainable process

00:04:21.679 --> 00:04:24.160
in that minimum process, you're gonna burn people out.

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:25.760
You're gonna frustrate a lot of people.

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:27.619
Your stakeholders aren't gonna be very happy.

00:04:27.619 --> 00:04:30.720
So we gotta just make sure it's not just viable effective,

00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:32.500
but also viable sustainable.

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:34.399
So something to keep in mind as we're talking

00:04:34.399 --> 00:04:36.720
about our high level process.

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:39.600
And then really the biggest word here I think is minimal.

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:42.440
As someone that's been in process for a long time,

00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:44.739
I actually find that too much process

00:04:44.739 --> 00:04:47.260
actually chokes things and you're actually looking

00:04:47.260 --> 00:04:50.220
for that sweet spot where it's enough process

00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:52.859
to keep people organized, coordinating well,

00:04:52.859 --> 00:04:55.339
whether that's outside teams or within your team,

00:04:55.339 --> 00:04:57.100
but not so much that it's actually

00:04:57.100 --> 00:04:59.779
like a lot of waste happening, a lot of friction,

00:04:59.779 --> 00:05:01.500
and a lot of the meetings feel bad

00:05:01.500 --> 00:05:02.720
and all that kind of stuff.

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:05.660
So we're looking to do a minimal process

00:05:05.660 --> 00:05:09.339
to give the team the room to do their best work.

00:05:09.339 --> 00:05:10.980
And the more we weigh them down,

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:12.779
the harder time that's gonna be to do.

00:05:12.779 --> 00:05:14.100
So we're looking for minimal,

00:05:14.100 --> 00:05:16.820
but still viable for our process.

00:05:16.820 --> 00:05:19.260
Okay, everybody's process is gonna be

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:20.299
a little bit different.

00:05:20.299 --> 00:05:22.220
I'm gonna use a lot of agile terminology.

00:05:22.220 --> 00:05:23.720
Hopefully folks are familiar.

00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:25.720
It's kind of the most standard one.

00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:27.739
There's a big question about little A agile

00:05:27.739 --> 00:05:29.859
and being flexible and big A agile,

00:05:29.859 --> 00:05:32.660
which turns into scrum and safe and all these big ones.

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:34.260
I really mean the little A agile,

00:05:34.260 --> 00:05:36.779
but let's distill down a hypothetical,

00:05:36.779 --> 00:05:38.700
very high level process.

00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:41.720
And one that kind of applies to everything

00:05:41.720 --> 00:05:44.600
and is really focused on handoff points.

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:47.420
My experience, we're just coming off the Olympics.

00:05:47.420 --> 00:05:50.359
It's handoffs between people and groups

00:05:50.359 --> 00:05:53.679
where friction and pain and mistakes happen a lot.

00:05:53.679 --> 00:05:56.040
So we're gonna talk about our high level process,

00:05:56.040 --> 00:05:58.480
mostly focused on those handoff points.

00:05:58.480 --> 00:06:00.799
Cause some of the, am I building a pipeline?

00:06:00.799 --> 00:06:02.880
What am I building a model?

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:04.279
Am I delivering this report?

00:06:04.279 --> 00:06:07.480
There's a lot of details that aren't as important

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:09.160
and kind of get more focus.

00:06:09.160 --> 00:06:11.179
Whereas I think some of these handoff points

00:06:11.220 --> 00:06:12.100
can be more important.

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:14.579
So first step is just gathering, right?

00:06:14.579 --> 00:06:16.420
What do we actually need to do?

00:06:16.420 --> 00:06:17.899
What do we actually need to do?

00:06:17.899 --> 00:06:18.899
Then we're doing the shit.

00:06:18.899 --> 00:06:19.859
We're getting the stuff done.

00:06:19.859 --> 00:06:22.339
All that details, building things, testing things,

00:06:22.339 --> 00:06:23.380
delivering things.

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:25.100
Well, and then delivering things

00:06:25.100 --> 00:06:28.420
and deliver profit for South Park fans out there.

00:06:28.420 --> 00:06:30.299
You know, the underpants known had it, right?

00:06:30.299 --> 00:06:32.500
You know, you deliver, you get your profit.

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:34.100
Everybody's happy.

00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:35.579
So we're gonna break down each of these steps

00:06:35.579 --> 00:06:39.179
just a little bit, thinking about the friction part,

00:06:39.260 --> 00:06:40.179
what can go wrong?

00:06:40.179 --> 00:06:41.579
When does it feel bad?

00:06:41.579 --> 00:06:43.420
And like saying, hey, is there ways

00:06:43.420 --> 00:06:44.540
to make that more minimal,

00:06:44.540 --> 00:06:48.739
to give the team room to breathe, do their best work?

00:06:48.739 --> 00:06:51.299
Okay, so we're in the gathering step, right?

00:06:51.299 --> 00:06:52.739
We have stakeholders.

00:06:52.739 --> 00:06:55.299
Some of them are maybe obvious and noisy

00:06:55.299 --> 00:06:57.059
and close and demanding,

00:06:57.059 --> 00:06:59.619
but some of them may be really important and further away.

00:06:59.619 --> 00:07:01.779
So, you know, management may have some ideas,

00:07:01.779 --> 00:07:02.739
probably usually do.

00:07:02.739 --> 00:07:03.660
They're funding a group.

00:07:03.660 --> 00:07:05.339
They want certain things to happen,

00:07:05.339 --> 00:07:06.660
but maybe it's users.

00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:08.660
Maybe it's a different analyst group.

00:07:08.660 --> 00:07:10.739
There can be a lot of different stakeholders

00:07:10.739 --> 00:07:13.179
and it's really important to think about

00:07:13.179 --> 00:07:15.100
who those stakeholders are.

00:07:15.100 --> 00:07:18.579
How are you getting input from that particular stakeholder?

00:07:18.579 --> 00:07:21.260
And are you getting it at the right level

00:07:21.260 --> 00:07:22.859
of granularity, right?

00:07:22.859 --> 00:07:25.299
So if someone's further away,

00:07:25.299 --> 00:07:28.059
you really wanna ask them for missions.

00:07:28.059 --> 00:07:30.579
You don't want them detailing exactly what they want,

00:07:30.579 --> 00:07:32.820
but rather what are they trying to accomplish?

00:07:32.820 --> 00:07:34.940
And then the closer they are to your process

00:07:34.940 --> 00:07:36.540
and your team and your results,

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:38.739
the more involved they can be in the details.

00:07:38.739 --> 00:07:41.500
So again, sometimes friction is a misunderstanding

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:43.899
about what needs to get delivered,

00:07:43.899 --> 00:07:46.339
changing the order of what's the most important things.

00:07:46.339 --> 00:07:48.339
Most teams have too much going on.

00:07:48.339 --> 00:07:51.059
And so it's important to kind of order those things properly.

00:07:51.059 --> 00:07:52.980
But if you're looking at stakeholders,

00:07:52.980 --> 00:07:55.140
the level of detail, how close they are,

00:07:55.140 --> 00:07:58.059
and you're pushing up the mission, right?

00:07:58.059 --> 00:07:59.540
You're making it a little more abstract

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:02.179
and giving the team room to decide how to do it,

00:08:02.179 --> 00:08:04.339
you're gonna get your best results.

00:08:04.339 --> 00:08:05.820
So again, you wanna get the detail

00:08:05.820 --> 00:08:07.980
to match where it's coming from

00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:10.339
and give the team room to figure it out.

00:08:10.339 --> 00:08:12.299
The people closest to the problem,

00:08:12.299 --> 00:08:14.579
as much room as you can afford to give them

00:08:14.579 --> 00:08:16.779
to make good decisions, be effective about it,

00:08:16.779 --> 00:08:19.339
make the hard trade-offs in the trenches

00:08:19.339 --> 00:08:21.859
that really promote effectiveness.

00:08:22.820 --> 00:08:25.779
So along the way, I have a bunch of QR codes here.

00:08:25.779 --> 00:08:28.260
For me, leadership is like lots of little lessons

00:08:28.260 --> 00:08:30.420
and then you practice and then you get a few more.

00:08:30.420 --> 00:08:33.419
So this will be up on GitHub, you can find these.

00:08:33.419 --> 00:08:35.659
But along the way, I put up a ton of QR codes.

00:08:35.659 --> 00:08:38.580
Maybe if you get a few of them along the way,

00:08:38.580 --> 00:08:40.820
a nibble here and there will serve you well.

00:08:41.979 --> 00:08:44.299
So a quick story, I'm working with the Shiny team.

00:08:44.299 --> 00:08:46.179
I joined a little over two years ago

00:08:46.179 --> 00:08:48.340
and we actually had a problem in this area.

00:08:49.380 --> 00:08:52.419
We were practicing, and it was really Joe Chang.

00:08:52.419 --> 00:08:56.140
Joe Chang was practicing a guilt-driven development.

00:08:56.140 --> 00:08:58.299
He had his process reflect

00:08:58.299 --> 00:09:00.299
what he thought he was supposed to do.

00:09:00.299 --> 00:09:02.940
And what a very traditional QA person was telling him

00:09:03.340 --> 00:09:04.179
what he was supposed to do.

00:09:04.179 --> 00:09:07.539
So it was stories of a certain type

00:09:07.539 --> 00:09:10.299
and lots of steps on the Kanban process

00:09:10.299 --> 00:09:12.900
and lots of acceptance things having to happen.

00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:15.020
And frankly, it was frustrating the team.

00:09:15.020 --> 00:09:16.539
It really wasn't working well.

00:09:16.539 --> 00:09:19.580
They were feeling like it was a lot of time wasting.

00:09:19.580 --> 00:09:20.940
The Shiny team is blessed

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:22.619
with a lot of really senior folks

00:09:22.619 --> 00:09:24.099
that are serving themselves.

00:09:24.099 --> 00:09:25.940
They kind of know what needs to happen.

00:09:25.940 --> 00:09:28.739
So the best thing to give them was a high-level feature.

00:09:28.739 --> 00:09:31.179
Let them figure out how to deliberate what it is,

00:09:31.179 --> 00:09:33.659
interact with others on the team to refine it,

00:09:33.659 --> 00:09:37.299
and then own the QA process, the quality process,

00:09:37.299 --> 00:09:39.659
and then pull in some help when they need it.

00:09:39.659 --> 00:09:41.580
So a little non-traditional.

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:44.500
And as we switched to that and Karan joined the team,

00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:45.780
he's been an amazing QA person.

00:09:45.780 --> 00:09:46.940
He gets pulled in.

00:09:46.940 --> 00:09:47.780
It's flexible.

00:09:47.780 --> 00:09:48.859
We'll figure it out with them.

00:09:48.859 --> 00:09:52.059
Not asking for a ton of documentation up front.

00:09:52.059 --> 00:09:54.580
The team has really sped up, been happier,

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:56.299
and it's been working out really, really well.

00:09:56.299 --> 00:09:58.419
So we've made some really good progress on that front.

00:09:58.419 --> 00:09:59.299
We've got to keep going.

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:01.260
I have too much content.

00:10:01.260 --> 00:10:02.820
So let's go.

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:04.099
The next step, the doing.

00:10:04.099 --> 00:10:05.739
I don't want to get into the details of the doing.

00:10:05.739 --> 00:10:08.539
You all know what the doing looks like on your team

00:10:08.539 --> 00:10:10.460
in the actual activities,

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:14.299
but we can think about how do we organize it

00:10:14.299 --> 00:10:17.780
in a way that helps the team do their best work.

00:10:17.780 --> 00:10:19.299
And I think one of the ways to do that

00:10:19.299 --> 00:10:22.780
is to make as much space as you can get away with

00:10:22.780 --> 00:10:23.780
in your context.

00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:24.619
So what is that?

00:10:24.619 --> 00:10:25.460
That's for the who.

00:10:25.460 --> 00:10:27.940
You don't want the same person doing the work

00:10:27.940 --> 00:10:30.460
again and again and again and being stuck in a niche

00:10:30.460 --> 00:10:32.460
because they're going to feel stifled

00:10:32.460 --> 00:10:34.020
and you're not going to have redundancy.

00:10:34.020 --> 00:10:36.099
If they're not available, what happens to that?

00:10:36.099 --> 00:10:38.780
So even if it's not the most efficient in the moment

00:10:38.780 --> 00:10:42.099
in the big picture, by giving space for who,

00:10:42.099 --> 00:10:43.820
you're going to actually help the team.

00:10:43.820 --> 00:10:46.380
Your process is going to help the team be healthier,

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:48.219
deliver better, be happier.

00:10:48.219 --> 00:10:51.979
And happy teams get three, five, 10 times more done

00:10:51.979 --> 00:10:53.460
than ones that are frustrated.

00:10:54.380 --> 00:10:56.380
We also want to make room in the what and the how.

00:10:56.380 --> 00:10:57.219
We don't want to dictate.

00:10:57.219 --> 00:10:59.219
I'm a huge fan of pairing on stuff.

00:10:59.219 --> 00:11:01.500
A lot of data says more gets done,

00:11:01.500 --> 00:11:03.460
higher quality, people learn,

00:11:03.460 --> 00:11:04.820
but not everybody wants to do that.

00:11:04.820 --> 00:11:08.260
So again, we want to give the team as much room as we can

00:11:08.260 --> 00:11:10.659
and not dictate how they're going to do.

00:11:10.659 --> 00:11:12.619
And I already talked about that idea of features

00:11:12.619 --> 00:11:15.340
at the right level where they have room to make decisions

00:11:15.340 --> 00:11:17.260
and do the best results.

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:19.619
So that's some of the doing aspects of it.

00:11:20.780 --> 00:11:23.859
The other kind of a friction that I commonly see

00:11:23.859 --> 00:11:25.500
is meeting dread.

00:11:25.500 --> 00:11:27.739
Where you have that meeting on your schedule,

00:11:27.739 --> 00:11:29.179
you see it tomorrow and you're like,

00:11:29.179 --> 00:11:32.219
oh gosh, I have to survive another one of those.

00:11:32.219 --> 00:11:34.619
Okay, that's a pretty good sign that there's friction,

00:11:34.619 --> 00:11:36.260
that there's bad things happening.

00:11:36.260 --> 00:11:38.580
So if you're in charge of that, or even if you're not,

00:11:38.580 --> 00:11:40.140
and you're just kind of interested

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:42.179
in helping the team get better,

00:11:42.179 --> 00:11:45.500
it's really important to think about the meeting's purpose,

00:11:45.500 --> 00:11:47.419
the frequency it happens,

00:11:47.419 --> 00:11:49.460
and really who needs to be there.

00:11:49.460 --> 00:11:50.700
Sometimes new meetings start,

00:11:50.700 --> 00:11:52.780
lots of people feel left out, they want to join.

00:11:52.780 --> 00:11:53.780
The bigger the meeting,

00:11:53.780 --> 00:11:56.140
the less likely it is to be effective.

00:11:56.140 --> 00:11:59.260
And it's something to really keep in mind on that front.

00:11:59.260 --> 00:12:02.179
So again, we're coordinating in this step.

00:12:02.179 --> 00:12:03.940
That's where a lot of the friction's gonna come,

00:12:03.940 --> 00:12:05.500
those handoffs, that coordination,

00:12:05.500 --> 00:12:06.979
the getting on the same page.

00:12:08.299 --> 00:12:11.659
So one other little shiny story on this one.

00:12:11.659 --> 00:12:14.020
We were doing our guilt-driven development.

00:12:14.020 --> 00:12:15.580
We had dailies every day.

00:12:15.580 --> 00:12:17.859
It was eight people on the team at that point.

00:12:17.859 --> 00:12:19.820
It's gone up and down a little bit.

00:12:19.820 --> 00:12:20.859
It was too much.

00:12:20.859 --> 00:12:22.179
Everybody was bored.

00:12:22.219 --> 00:12:23.859
Eight people is too much to know

00:12:23.859 --> 00:12:25.619
what's going on with that many people.

00:12:25.619 --> 00:12:27.380
So everybody's just waiting their turn,

00:12:27.380 --> 00:12:29.780
spewing out what they tried to do yesterday.

00:12:29.780 --> 00:12:31.940
They would start to feel similar day after day,

00:12:31.940 --> 00:12:33.299
doing bigger tasks.

00:12:33.299 --> 00:12:34.460
So it really was not working.

00:12:34.460 --> 00:12:36.340
There was a lot of friction on it.

00:12:36.340 --> 00:12:39.020
We started by first separating into two sub-teams

00:12:39.020 --> 00:12:41.820
so you can kind of track what's going on with four people.

00:12:41.820 --> 00:12:43.059
It's a little more reasonable.

00:12:43.059 --> 00:12:45.780
You can get some context, understand what's up.

00:12:46.820 --> 00:12:48.859
But now we've even kind of pushed past that,

00:12:48.859 --> 00:12:52.219
and we've decided to try and do it with context pairs.

00:12:52.219 --> 00:12:55.099
So a senior dev, a Carson, a Barry grabs,

00:12:55.099 --> 00:12:57.179
like, hey, this is the feature for the next release.

00:12:57.179 --> 00:12:58.460
I'm the lead on it.

00:12:58.460 --> 00:13:01.299
And we add a second person as the context partner on it.

00:13:01.299 --> 00:13:04.020
So they are there for code reviews,

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:06.419
for brainstorming, for working together on it.

00:13:06.419 --> 00:13:07.539
So you want two people.

00:13:07.539 --> 00:13:09.659
You don't want just one person responsible,

00:13:09.659 --> 00:13:10.859
but you don't need four people

00:13:10.859 --> 00:13:13.500
all pretending they understand all the nuances

00:13:13.500 --> 00:13:16.020
and what's going on and why all the trade-offs were made.

00:13:16.020 --> 00:13:17.340
So that's been working pretty well,

00:13:17.340 --> 00:13:20.219
but that's something that we're in progress on.

00:13:20.219 --> 00:13:22.260
So delivery.

00:13:22.260 --> 00:13:24.140
Not going to say too much about this.

00:13:24.140 --> 00:13:27.020
Obviously, you need to ship whatever ship means for you

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:30.900
into that pipeline, that R package, that report.

00:13:30.900 --> 00:13:32.900
But there's other aspects,

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:35.419
and Alan had kind of referred to some of those,

00:13:35.419 --> 00:13:38.020
of beyond just what did I ship

00:13:38.020 --> 00:13:40.179
is actually thinking back to the stakeholders

00:13:40.179 --> 00:13:43.099
and involving them and doing a little bit of storytelling.

00:13:43.099 --> 00:13:45.700
And this is an area really often neglected.

00:13:45.700 --> 00:13:48.500
And by spending a little time saying,

00:13:48.500 --> 00:13:50.700
this is what we delivered, this is why.

00:13:50.700 --> 00:13:53.979
And if there was a problem and this was the problem,

00:13:53.979 --> 00:13:56.700
you can really pull those stakeholders in.

00:13:56.700 --> 00:13:58.020
They can see the value.

00:13:58.020 --> 00:13:59.859
The team can feel really good

00:13:59.859 --> 00:14:01.380
about what they're accomplishing,

00:14:01.380 --> 00:14:02.580
not just ship, ship, ship,

00:14:02.580 --> 00:14:04.500
and then dot, think about it from there.

00:14:04.500 --> 00:14:06.979
So it's something, it's also really interesting to me

00:14:06.979 --> 00:14:08.739
because this is an area that's exciting

00:14:08.739 --> 00:14:10.780
because one person,

00:14:10.780 --> 00:14:12.619
like a lot of those other steps I'm talking about

00:14:12.619 --> 00:14:14.940
involve a lot of coordination, a lot of changes.

00:14:14.940 --> 00:14:16.859
It can be challenging to do,

00:14:16.859 --> 00:14:19.219
but in this idea of delivering

00:14:19.219 --> 00:14:21.179
and then doing a little work around the delivery

00:14:21.179 --> 00:14:22.859
to make sure stakeholders are with you

00:14:22.859 --> 00:14:26.219
and they understand what's up spoken in their language

00:14:26.219 --> 00:14:29.140
and at the right level of granularity for them,

00:14:29.140 --> 00:14:30.140
that's really powerful.

00:14:30.140 --> 00:14:31.059
You can do that.

00:14:31.059 --> 00:14:33.179
And you don't have to be the formal manager.

00:14:33.179 --> 00:14:34.619
I don't know of any manager.

00:14:34.619 --> 00:14:36.380
I certainly wouldn't be one of them.

00:14:36.380 --> 00:14:37.539
If someone on the team was like,

00:14:37.539 --> 00:14:39.780
hey, I think a little bit of a summary

00:14:39.780 --> 00:14:41.260
of what we shipped in that last one,

00:14:41.260 --> 00:14:43.659
but that's set well for this exec team

00:14:43.659 --> 00:14:47.739
or this outside user group would go a long way,

00:14:47.739 --> 00:14:48.780
that's gonna be embraced.

00:14:48.780 --> 00:14:51.380
So a little effort, you can improve the process.

00:14:51.380 --> 00:14:54.179
And I think that's a great way to explore

00:14:54.179 --> 00:14:57.140
if this whole leadership organizational

00:14:57.140 --> 00:14:59.739
kind of thing calls to you.

00:14:59.739 --> 00:15:02.059
Okay, I need to hurry up.

00:15:02.059 --> 00:15:04.140
So again, we have our process.

00:15:04.140 --> 00:15:05.380
You have more details in it,

00:15:05.380 --> 00:15:07.179
but I talked about the abstract one.

00:15:07.179 --> 00:15:10.059
You have to accept that there is no right process.

00:15:10.059 --> 00:15:12.500
The people, the situation, what you try to do,

00:15:12.500 --> 00:15:13.940
it's a moving target.

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:16.500
And we wanna play along with that moving target

00:15:16.500 --> 00:15:17.580
and try things.

00:15:17.580 --> 00:15:19.700
We're gonna do that as a group activity.

00:15:19.700 --> 00:15:21.099
We're gonna decide together

00:15:21.099 --> 00:15:23.020
where the pain and the friction is

00:15:23.020 --> 00:15:25.059
and what we might wanna be able to do about it.

00:15:25.059 --> 00:15:27.260
And then we're gonna formulate experiments.

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:29.580
We don't know what will work better.

00:15:29.580 --> 00:15:32.460
We're gonna theorize something, try something,

00:15:32.460 --> 00:15:34.820
and then repeat that over and over and over

00:15:34.820 --> 00:15:39.380
and slowly, continuous improvement get better over time.

00:15:39.419 --> 00:15:42.940
So just to kind of put this in a little bit agile terms,

00:15:42.940 --> 00:15:44.299
maybe this is something people know about,

00:15:44.299 --> 00:15:46.900
but hopefully you're doing retrospectives, right?

00:15:46.900 --> 00:15:50.380
So you're looking back kind of what worked in this release,

00:15:50.380 --> 00:15:53.619
what happened, what went well, what didn't go well,

00:15:53.619 --> 00:15:55.700
what could we do better, bad, sad, glad,

00:15:55.700 --> 00:15:58.260
some of those retros that are kind of standard ones,

00:15:58.260 --> 00:16:00.619
standard retrospectives could get a little stale.

00:16:00.619 --> 00:16:04.979
So I'm gonna say, be cheeky, do one that's very directed.

00:16:04.979 --> 00:16:07.380
We wanna make the process work for the team.

00:16:07.380 --> 00:16:09.260
So you're gonna come out and ask them,

00:16:10.140 --> 00:16:13.419
which part of our process kills your soul the most?

00:16:13.419 --> 00:16:14.580
And if you get those answers,

00:16:14.580 --> 00:16:15.780
you know where the friction is

00:16:15.780 --> 00:16:18.780
and you have something that, okay, let's talk about that.

00:16:18.780 --> 00:16:20.539
What possibly dumb ass way

00:16:20.539 --> 00:16:22.419
could it be a little bit less crappy, right?

00:16:22.419 --> 00:16:23.580
We're not gonna fix it all at once.

00:16:23.580 --> 00:16:25.020
We're gonna do a little experiment.

00:16:25.020 --> 00:16:26.500
So how can we do that?

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:29.500
And then, hey, let's take that vague idea of like,

00:16:29.500 --> 00:16:32.179
oh, it'd be better if, and say, here's an experiment.

00:16:32.179 --> 00:16:33.460
Here's something to try.

00:16:33.460 --> 00:16:35.099
Let's give that a shot.

00:16:35.099 --> 00:16:36.380
Let's see how that goes.

00:16:36.380 --> 00:16:38.700
So we're gonna do a couple of little experiments.

00:16:39.140 --> 00:16:40.460
We're not gonna have too many going on at once

00:16:40.460 --> 00:16:42.219
and we're gonna find our way

00:16:42.219 --> 00:16:44.099
towards a better process over time.

00:16:44.099 --> 00:16:45.820
If you need a little more structure than that,

00:16:45.820 --> 00:16:47.780
you can try the popcorn method.

00:16:47.780 --> 00:16:50.580
Claudio Peroni kind of came up with it.

00:16:50.580 --> 00:16:51.900
It's a big Kanban board.

00:16:51.900 --> 00:16:53.859
There's seven lanes that you go through.

00:16:53.859 --> 00:16:55.820
The first three, we really talked about,

00:16:55.820 --> 00:16:58.900
problems and observations, what are options to fix it?

00:16:58.900 --> 00:17:01.380
What are possible experiments you could try and do?

00:17:01.380 --> 00:17:04.540
And then the corn really just takes you to the commit

00:17:04.540 --> 00:17:06.180
and ongoing and reviewing

00:17:06.180 --> 00:17:08.540
and kind of keeping that train going.

00:17:09.380 --> 00:17:10.979
Great, more work.

00:17:10.979 --> 00:17:12.619
We have to work on our process too.

00:17:12.619 --> 00:17:14.859
It's not enough that we have too much to deliver.

00:17:14.859 --> 00:17:17.540
There's so many excuses for reasons not to do this.

00:17:17.540 --> 00:17:21.420
I'm gonna run through a few and then we can wrap up here.

00:17:22.660 --> 00:17:25.979
The biggest one I always hear is, it's not us.

00:17:25.979 --> 00:17:28.699
It's not us that are causing the problem, it's them.

00:17:28.699 --> 00:17:30.819
It kind of doesn't matter who the them is,

00:17:30.819 --> 00:17:32.500
but it's them, it's their problem.

00:17:32.500 --> 00:17:33.819
Well, guess what then?

00:17:33.819 --> 00:17:36.339
Time to work together, collaborate,

00:17:36.339 --> 00:17:37.900
and you're gonna do your pop.

00:17:37.939 --> 00:17:39.380
What's killing your soul?

00:17:39.380 --> 00:17:40.420
What could we do better?

00:17:40.420 --> 00:17:42.900
What experiments with them in the room?

00:17:42.900 --> 00:17:45.900
They're part of your process, pull in the right key people,

00:17:45.900 --> 00:17:47.900
and you can really make progress on that.

00:17:47.900 --> 00:17:52.060
Not them, make it about us and get the us in the room.

00:17:52.060 --> 00:17:54.660
We don't have time for this, we're overloaded.

00:17:54.660 --> 00:17:56.420
Well, if you stick to a process

00:17:56.420 --> 00:17:57.819
and you don't give more visibility

00:17:57.819 --> 00:17:59.979
into what's going on to the people that need it,

00:17:59.979 --> 00:18:01.579
you're gonna just get worse over time.

00:18:01.579 --> 00:18:02.579
You're gonna burn people out,

00:18:02.579 --> 00:18:04.140
you're not gonna make progress.

00:18:05.260 --> 00:18:07.060
Hey, we already tried fixing this.

00:18:07.060 --> 00:18:08.300
We tried these other things.

00:18:08.300 --> 00:18:11.420
We had process improvement before, get over it.

00:18:11.420 --> 00:18:12.900
Well, the fact of the matter is,

00:18:12.900 --> 00:18:14.660
failing, you may have failed.

00:18:14.660 --> 00:18:17.219
You may have tried it, but you need to learn from it.

00:18:17.219 --> 00:18:18.339
Was it a bad idea?

00:18:18.339 --> 00:18:19.619
Was it too ambitious?

00:18:19.619 --> 00:18:21.219
Was it a lack of follow-through?

00:18:21.219 --> 00:18:23.099
You gotta learn from those things and improve.

00:18:23.099 --> 00:18:24.699
So just the fact that something didn't work out

00:18:24.699 --> 00:18:26.459
once before doesn't mean you give up.

00:18:26.459 --> 00:18:28.300
And then, oh, management won't let us.

00:18:28.300 --> 00:18:31.339
They make us follow some elaborate scheme,

00:18:31.339 --> 00:18:34.060
they bring in experts and consultants and they dictate it.

00:18:34.060 --> 00:18:36.380
Well, don't disempower you and your team.

00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:37.979
If you're doing some experimenting,

00:18:37.979 --> 00:18:39.579
if you're trying to make things better,

00:18:39.579 --> 00:18:41.060
there's no management team that's gonna say,

00:18:41.060 --> 00:18:41.900
don't do that.

00:18:41.900 --> 00:18:43.660
You start within the strictures they set

00:18:43.660 --> 00:18:45.180
and you make progress.

00:18:45.180 --> 00:18:46.819
And by the way, just don't ask for permission.

00:18:46.819 --> 00:18:48.900
Just try it, tweak things, it'll get better.

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:50.180
The results will pay for itself.

00:18:50.180 --> 00:18:51.660
It'll be good.

00:18:51.660 --> 00:18:53.859
Okay, this is the Agile process,

00:18:53.859 --> 00:18:55.939
the Agile manifesto specifically.

00:18:55.939 --> 00:18:56.780
If you look through it,

00:18:56.780 --> 00:18:58.819
I think you'll see a lot of the kind of themes

00:18:58.819 --> 00:19:01.900
I'm hitting on, individuals and interactions.

00:19:01.900 --> 00:19:04.900
Working software, we can say a working process.

00:19:04.900 --> 00:19:07.180
Customer collaboration, I really think in this case,

00:19:07.180 --> 00:19:08.739
it's stakeholder collaboration

00:19:08.739 --> 00:19:11.020
and then responding to change, right?

00:19:11.020 --> 00:19:13.859
So this is really Agile, this is the heart of it

00:19:13.859 --> 00:19:16.099
and apply it to your process can be great.

00:19:16.099 --> 00:19:19.739
So again, channeling my Dr. Seuss,

00:19:19.739 --> 00:19:23.140
repeating that same idea that I'm asking you all to try.

00:19:23.140 --> 00:19:25.859
In a lively hub where ideas fly in dart,

00:19:25.859 --> 00:19:29.140
the team map their processes, each playing their part.

00:19:29.140 --> 00:19:31.140
Keep it all light, let's empower and grow,

00:19:31.140 --> 00:19:33.579
getting sure that our output has value to show.

00:19:33.579 --> 00:19:36.540
They tweaked and they tested and with agility played,

00:19:36.540 --> 00:19:39.500
finding new ways for their efforts could sway.

00:19:39.500 --> 00:19:41.939
From shadows of old, they emerged step-by-step,

00:19:41.939 --> 00:19:45.619
their process now streamlined, efficient and light.

00:19:45.619 --> 00:19:47.380
So thank you all so much.

00:19:47.380 --> 00:19:49.140
Please reach out if you're on this journey

00:19:49.140 --> 00:19:50.540
or even thinking about it.

00:19:50.540 --> 00:19:52.739
And here's some resources that I just love

00:19:52.739 --> 00:19:55.060
and have used, gone back to over and over.

00:19:55.060 --> 00:19:56.180
Thank you very much.

00:19:58.739 --> 00:20:02.900
All right, we were exactly on time.

00:20:02.900 --> 00:20:04.699
I just wanted to remind everyone

00:20:04.699 --> 00:20:07.020
that there is a Discord server

00:20:07.020 --> 00:20:11.020
where if you want to continue the conversation, you can.

00:20:11.020 --> 00:20:12.859
Before Andrew steps away,

00:20:12.859 --> 00:20:14.459
there was one question from Discord

00:20:14.459 --> 00:20:15.380
and everyone wants to know,

00:20:15.380 --> 00:20:17.619
where did you get the pictures from?

00:20:17.619 --> 00:20:20.900
Oh, just playing with Mid Journey.

00:20:20.900 --> 00:20:22.579
It turns out it's pretty good at doing that.

00:20:22.579 --> 00:20:23.819
A little bit of Dr. Seuss

00:20:23.819 --> 00:20:25.780
and you have to use Mid Journey, by the way,

00:20:25.780 --> 00:20:27.819
because Dali will say, oh, you can't say Dr. Seuss,

00:20:27.819 --> 00:20:28.859
that's like protected.

00:20:28.859 --> 00:20:31.260
So Mid Journey, but it was fun

00:20:31.260 --> 00:20:33.660
and I probably spent too much time on that, but.

